{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659782"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:15:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20901"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20901"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.1,0,0.65,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13776"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13776"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79452"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12470"},{"type":"tags","id":"12724"},{"type":"tags","id":"12725"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33208"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA laboratory test is used to confirm the presence of specific antimicrobial antibodies in a patient\u0027s serum. The test involves separating proteins by electrophoresis, transferring them to a membrane, and then detecting antibody binding to specific target antigens. This test is typically performed after an initial positive screening result to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory techniques is described above?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Precipitation test","Enzyme immunoassay","Eastern blot test","Western blot test","Complement fixation test"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description matches a \u003Cstrong\u003EWestern blot test\u003C/strong\u003E, which involves separating proteins by electrophoresis, transferring them to a membrane, and then detecting antibody binding to specific target antigens. Western blots are characterized by high specificity and are commonly used as confirmatory tests after initial positive screening results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrecipitation test\u003C/strong\u003E - This test relies on the formation of visible precipitates when antibodies bind to soluble antigens. It does not involve electrophoresis or membrane transfer.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnzyme immunoassay\u003C/strong\u003E - While this technique (including ELISA) also detects antibodies, it typically uses microwell plates rather than membrane transfer of electrophoresed proteins. It is often used as an initial screening test before Western blot confirmation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEastern blot test\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a modification of Western blotting used specifically for detecting post-translational modifications like glycosylation and lipid modifications, not for routine antibody detection as described in the stem.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement fixation test\u003C/strong\u003E - This test measures the reduction of complement activity following antigen-antibody reactions. It does not involve protein separation or membrane transfer.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWestern blot tests are particularly valuable for confirming diagnoses of infections such as HIV, where false positive screening tests can occur. The high specificity of Western blots comes from their ability to detect antibodies against specific protein components of pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Western blot tests detect specific antibodies by their reaction with target antigens that have been immobilized onto a membrane.","Western blot tests have high specificity but often lower sensitivity than screening tests like enzyme immunoassays.","Western blot tests are commonly used to confirm positive results from initial screening tests."],"references":["Vazquez-Pertejo MT, Bush LM. Immunologic Tests for Infectious Disease. Merck Manual Professional Edition. January 2025. Available from: https://www.merckmanuals.com/professional/infectious-diseases/laboratory-diagnosis-of-infectious-disease/immunologic-tests-for-infectious-disease"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79452"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20901"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79452"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:56:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:59:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13776"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96837"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationsh